{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654293"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:51:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18612"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18612","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18612"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76431"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18612"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61928"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10261"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26338"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76431"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contraction of skeletal muscle fibres involves molecular interactions between protein filaments within the sarcomere. This process depends on both calcium ions and adenosine triphosphate (ATP).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of skeletal muscle contraction?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thin filaments actively move across stationary thick filaments","Calcium ions directly drive filament movement","Regulatory proteins actively generate contractile force","Myosin cross-bridges pull actin filaments using ATP-derived energy","ATP causes shortening of the contractile proteins"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe contractile mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Emyosin cross-bridges pulling actin filaments using ATP-derived energy\u003C/strong\u003E. When ATP is hydrolysed, the myosin head undergoes a conformational change that generates force, moving the thin filaments towards the sarcomere centre.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThin filaments actively move across stationary thick filaments\u003C/strong\u003E - Thin filaments are passive structures; force is generated by myosin heads\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium ions directly drive filament movement\u003C/strong\u003E - Calcium only enables contraction by exposing binding sites; it does not generate movement\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulatory proteins actively generate contractile force\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteins like tropomyosin only regulate binding; they do not produce force\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EATP causes shortening of the contractile proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - The filaments maintain their length but slide relative to each other\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis process requires calcium ions to shift tropomyosin and expose binding sites on actin, while ATP powers the myosin head movements that generate contractile force.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Muscle contraction occurs when myosin heads form cross-bridges with actin filaments and undergo a power stroke.","ATP hydrolysis provides the energy needed for the conformational change in myosin heads during contraction.","Calcium ions enable contraction by removing tropomyosin\u0027s inhibitory effect on actin-myosin binding."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61928"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61928"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:58:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T13:59:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76431"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","u